  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "EM",
    "text": "When we came over to Los Angeles, he did work. He did go at night to school. And I did go to work USC as a technologist. And we raised three kids during the time he worked through university and became an electronic engineer. He did work at McDonnell Douglas 30 years. And unfortunately, in 1991, he became sick with cancer, and he is sick since. From 1992, he is not able to stand up or walk and especially the last two years, he is paralyzed. That is the life story of Rudy Mann. was in-- in the Jewish-- I mean, the Hungarian Army as a Jewish soldier. He was taken marching from Hungary to Mauthausen. And during the time, he was helping people who couldn't walk, risking his own life. And then someone put down a Torah, a small Torah. Rudy not able to remember where that happened during the march, but he was the only who wanted to carry the Torah farther and he did. He threw away his coat, because that was too heavy to carry the coat and the Torah. And finally, they arrived somewhere, what later was known Mauthausen, but he collapsed. He didn't remember when they arrived and what happened to the Torah. Many years ago, we did go to New York with Rudy. And we did go to see, not Ellis Island, but the Liberty of--",
